<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910419-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>910419-0002.</DOCID><HL>   Environmental Systems Says   Lobbyist Recanted Allegations</HL><DATE>04/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ESC</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><RE>ARKANSAS (AR)ARIZONA (AZ)</RE><LP>   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. -- Environmental Systems Co. said itreceived statements from a former lobbyist and from the Cityof Phoenix and Maricopa County retracting allegations thatthe company made payments to Arizona legislators to winsupport for a hazardous-waste disposal plant.   According to a story in the Phoenix Gazette, the lobbyist,Ernest Hoffman, allegedly told a police informant in Augustthat Environmental Systems encouraged him to make payments toArizona lawmakers to help get a permit for the facility.</LP><TEXT>   However, Mr. Hoffman, in a sworn affadavit, said thatneither Environmental Systems nor its president, JackForrest, ever suggested or requested that he do anythingimproper or illegal on their behalf. He also said in thestatement that he doesn't know of attempts to buy politicalfavors.   Mr. Hoffman was indicted in February on bribery chargesstemming from a sting operation investigating bribery,campaignlaw violations and money laundering in Arizona.   In a settlement of charges that the city and countydefamed the company and Mr. Forrest, the city, the county andthe county attorney issued a statement saying that its policeinformant didn't have any information to indicate thatEnvironmental Systems or its representatives engaged in anyimproper or illegal conduct.   Environmental Systems had denied the allegations and saidthat it employed Mr. Hoffman for just a few months beforereplacing him. Although Environmental Systems has investedabout $60 million in the hazardous-waste facility, to bebuilt about 30 miles from Phoenix, controversy over the planthas kept it from winning a permit to build it.</TEXT></DOC>